The Senate, at the beginning of the 36th Congress, still maintained a narrow [Democratic](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)) majority, a testament to its more conservative nature. However, by the end of its term, with the dramatic withdrawal of Southern members, the balance of power decisively shifted to the [Republicans](/Republican_Party_(United_States)). This transformation was not merely a change in party control but a stark reflection of the Union's disintegration. The "vacant" column at the end of the term tells a more profound story than any statistical breakdown ever could.

