#### Joint committees

These committees, composed of members from both chambers, were meant to foster cooperation, a concept that became increasingly elusive during this period.

*   [Enrolled Bills](/United_States_Congress_Joint_Committee_on_Enrolled_Bills) (Chairman: Sen. [Henry Haun](/Henry_Haun) then Sen. [Willard Saulsbury Sr.](/Willard_Saulsbury_Sr.))
*   [The Library](/United_States_Congress_Joint_Committee_on_the_Library) (Chairman: Rep. [John U. Pettit](/John_U._Pettit))
*   [Printing](/United_States_Congress_Joint_Committee_on_Printing) (Chairman: Rep. [John A. Gurley](/John_A._Gurley))
*   Making Arrangements for Inaugurating Washington's Statue, a committee dedicated to honoring the past at a time when the future was profoundly uncertain.

### Caucuses

Political caucuses served as internal party mechanisms, where strategies were forged and allegiances tested, especially within the increasingly divided Democratic Party.

*   [Democratic](/House_Democratic_Caucus) (House)
*   [Democratic](/Senate_Democratic_Caucus) (Senate)

### Employees

Even as the political superstructure groaned under immense strain, the underlying bureaucratic machinery, staffed by dedicated (or simply employed) individuals, continued its daily operations.

#### [Legislative branch agency](/List_of_federal_agencies_in_the_United_States) directors

*   [Architect of the Capitol](/Architect_of_the_Capitol): [Thomas U. Walter](/Thomas_U._Walter), overseeing the very structure that housed the nation's fracturing government.
*   [Librarian of Congress](/Librarian_of_Congress): [John Silva Meehan](/John_Silva_Meehan), safeguarding the nation's collective knowledge as its unity crumbled.

#### Senate

*   [Chaplain](/Chaplain_of_the_United_States_Senate): [Stephen P. Hill](/Stephen_P._Hill) ([Baptist](/Baptist)), until December 15, 1859.
*   [Phineas D. Gurley](/Phineas_D._Gurley) ([Presbyterian](/Presbyterianism)), elected December 15, 1859, tasked with offering spiritual guidance to a body seemingly beyond salvation.
*   [Secretary](/Secretary_of_the_United_States_Senate): [Asbury Dickins](/Asbury_Dickins), the chief administrative officer.
*   [Sergeant at Arms](/Sergeant_at_Arms_of_the_United_States_Senate): [Dunning R. McNair](/Dunning_R._McNair), responsible for maintaining order, a task that grew increasingly challenging.

#### House of Representatives

*   [Clerk](/Clerk_of_the_United_States_House_of_Representatives): [James C. Allen](/James_C._Allen), until February 3, 1860.
*   [John W. Forney](/John_W._Forney), elected February 3, 1860, taking over the crucial role of record-keeping.
*   [Chaplain](/Chaplain_of_the_United_States_House_of_Representatives): None. Perhaps they had given up on divine intervention for this particular chamber.
*   [Doorkeeper](/Doorkeeper_of_the_United_States_House_of_Representatives): Robert B. Hackney, until February 6, 1860.
*   George Marston, elected February 6, 1860, controlling access to a house increasingly divided against itself.
*   [Messenger](/Messenger_of_the_United_States_House_of_Representatives): Thaddeus Morrice
*   [Postmaster](/Postmaster_of_the_United_States_House_of_Representatives): Josiah M. Lucas
*   [Reading Clerks](/Reading_Clerk_of_the_United_States_House_of_Representatives): &#91; [data missing](/Wikipedia:Cleanup) &#93;
*   [Sergeant at Arms](/Sergeant_at_Arms_of_the_United_States_House_of_Representatives): [Adam J. Glossbrenner](/Adam_J._Glossbrenner), until February 3, 1860.
*   [Henry William Hoffman](/Henry_William_Hoffman), from February 3, 1860, assuming the heavy responsibility of maintaining decorum in a fractious environment.

